<subSubSection pageId="15" pageNumber="44" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="15.[794,1399,937,1313]" pageId="15" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[794,891,937,961]" pageId="15" pageNumber="44">Remarks</emphasis>
: The species is sufficiently described in SMETANA’S (1982) work on the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Erichson" authorityYear="1839" box="[1145,1297,969,993]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Xantholininae">Xantholininae</taxonomicName>
north of 
<collectingCountry box="[794,875,1001,1025]" name="Mexico" pageId="15" pageNumber="44">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="SMETANA, A." box="[884,1061,1001,1025]" pageId="15" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 389" refId="ref41499" refString="SMETANA, A. 1982: Revision of the subfamily Xantholininae of America North of Mexico (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). - Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada 12: 1 - 389." type="journal article" year="1982">SMETANA (1982)</bibRefCitation>
only mentioned the occurrence in 
<collectingRegion box="[821,898,1033,1057]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="15" pageNumber="44">Florida</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry box="[911,966,1033,1057]" name="United States of America" pageId="15" pageNumber="44">USA</collectingCountry>
) but the species also occurs in the northeastern region of the Neotropics such as 
<collectingCountry box="[1257,1399,1065,1089]" name="Bahamas" pageId="15" pageNumber="44">the Bahamas</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[843,900,1097,1121]" name="Cuba" pageId="15" pageNumber="44">Cuba</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="PECK, S. B." box="[919,1042,1097,1121]" pageId="15" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 248" refId="ref41367" refString="PECK, S. B. 2005: A checklist of the beetles of Cuba with data on distribution and bionomics (Insecta: Coleoptera). - Arthropods of Florida and Neighboring Land Areas 18: 1 - 248." type="journal article" year="2005">PECK 2005</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="SMETANA, A." box="[1062,1243,1097,1121]" pageId="15" pageNumber="44" pagination="1 - 389" refId="ref41499" refString="SMETANA, A. 1982: Revision of the subfamily Xantholininae of America North of Mexico (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae). - Memoirs of the Entomological Society of Canada 12: 1 - 389." type="journal article" year="1982">SMETANA (1982)</bibRefCitation>
described the species as uniformly testaceous to testaceo-brunneous. Within the material from 
<collectingCountry box="[1074,1212,1161,1185]" name="Bahamas" pageId="15" pageNumber="44">the Bahamas</collectingCountry>
a nearly blackish specimen was present. Among the neotropical species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="LECONTE" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[794,927,1225,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lithocharodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="floridanus">
<emphasis box="[794,927,1225,1249]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="44">L. floridanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the small size and the long second antennomere, which is longer than the third.
</paragraph>
